The ratio \(\frac{K}{L}\) is given by \(t^2 - t + 1\), where \(K\) is the area of the triangle with side lengths equal to the segments \(AP\), \(BQ\), and \(CR\), and \(L\) is the area of triangle \(ABC\).

This result is independent of the specific shape of triangle \(ABC\), as verified through coordinate geometry with different triangles (a right triangle and an equilateral triangle) and vector calculations. The expression \(t^2 - t + 1\) holds for \(0 < t < 1\).

\boxed{t^{2} - t + 1}
